# WordPress Elementor Transfer Pipeline
## Execution Guide — Single File

---

## STEP 1 — Build Content Map

**Trigger:** User sends a reference (screenshot or live URL of the design to replicate).

**What to do:**
- Analyze the reference thoroughly — every section, every element.
- Document ALL of the following:
  - All copy (headings, subheadings, body text, button labels, nav items, footers, disclaimers — everything)
  - All colors (backgrounds, text colors, button colors, borders — use hex codes)
  - All font sizes (in px or rem as seen)
  - All font families / font weights
  - Spacing clues (padding, gaps, margin estimates from visual inspection)
  - Layout notes (number of columns per row, flex direction, alignment)
  - Any icons, image placeholders, or media noted

**Write a file:**
Save all notes to: `scratch/content_map.md`

Format it clearly with sections matching the page layout (e.g. Hero, Features, Testimonials, CTA, Footer). Be exhaustive — this file is your source of truth for all copy and styling. You will refer to it in every subsequent step. Do NOT work from memory.

**Tell the user:** Content map is done, saved to scratch. Share the URL or screenshot of the Elementor layout page you built.

---

## STEP 2 — Extract Data IDs from Layout Page

**Trigger:** User sends the URL of their pre-built Elementor page (containers and widgets already in place, no real content yet).

**What to do:**
- Access the page source or use the Elementor REST API / page meta to retrieve the full `_elementor_data` JSON blob for that page.
- Parse the JSON and walk every node.
- For each widget, extract and record:
  - `id` (the Elementor widget/element ID)
  - `elType` (widget, column, section, container)
  - `widgetType` (heading, text-editor, button, image, etc.)
  - Any existing text content (even placeholder text) so you can match it to the content map
  - Its position context (what section it lives in, its order)

**Write a file:**
Save all extracted IDs and their mapping to: `scratch/data_ids.md`

Format it as a structured list, grouped by section, like:

```
## Hero Section
- ID: abc123 | widgetType: heading | placeholder: "Your Heading Here"
- ID: def456 | widgetType: text-editor | placeholder: "Subheading text"
- ID: ghi789 | widgetType: button | placeholder: "Click Me"

## Features Section
...
```

Cross-reference each widget ID to the corresponding copy entry in `scratch/content_map.md` so the mapping is explicit. Do NOT work from memory — always read from the scratch files.

**Tell the user:** Data extraction done. Moving to copy injection now.

---

## STEP 3 — Push Copy via REST API

**Trigger:** Both scratch files exist and are complete.

**What to do:**
- Read `scratch/content_map.md` — get all the copy.
- Read `scratch/data_ids.md` — get all the widget IDs and their section mapping.
- Retrieve the full `_elementor_data` JSON for the page via WordPress REST API:
  ```
  GET /wp-json/wp/v2/pages/{page_id}
  ```
  (or posts endpoint if it's a post type)
- Parse the `_elementor_data` field (it's a JSON string, decode it).
- Walk the parsed JSON and for each widget ID found in `scratch/data_ids.md`:
  - Replace the widget's content/text with the corresponding copy from `scratch/content_map.md`
  - For buttons: update `button_text`
  - For headings: update `title`
  - For text editors: update `editor`
  - For images: update `url` / `alt` if applicable
- Re-encode the entire `_elementor_data` back to a JSON string.
- Push it back via REST API:
  ```
  POST /wp-json/wp/v2/pages/{page_id}
  Body: { "meta": { "_elementor_data": "<updated JSON string>" } }
  ```
- Use Basic Auth or Application Password for authentication.

**Tell the user:** Copy has been pushed. Please review the page now and confirm everything looks correct — right copy in the right places. Once you give the green light, we move to styling.

---

## STEP 4 — Push CSS Styling via SSH

**Trigger:** User confirms copy looks good.

**What to do:**
- Read `scratch/content_map.md` — pull all colors, font sizes, font families, spacing values.
- Read `scratch/data_ids.md` — use the widget IDs to build targeted CSS selectors.
- Elementor widget selectors follow the pattern:
  ```css
  .elementor-element-{id} { ... }
  .elementor-element-{id} .elementor-widget-container { ... }
  .elementor-element-{id} h2 { ... }
  /* etc. */
  ```
- Write a complete CSS block covering:
  - Background colors per section/container
  - Text colors, font sizes, font weights, font families per widget
  - Button colors, hover states, border radius, padding
  - Section/container padding and gap values
  - Any additional visual details from the content map

- Connect via SSH to the WordPress server.
- Inject the CSS into the theme's custom CSS file or directly into `wp-content/uploads/elementor/css/post-{page_id}.css` (Elementor's generated CSS file for the page).
- Alternatively, append to the active theme's `style.css` or use the WordPress Customizer CSS endpoint if SSH injection is not preferred.

**Tell the user:** Styling has been pushed. Refresh the page and check it out — let me know if anything needs tweaking.

---

## Notes

- Always read from scratch files. Never rely on memory between steps.
- Scratch files live at: `scratch/content_map.md` and `scratch/data_ids.md`
- The `_elementor_data` field is a serialized JSON string — always decode before editing, always re-encode before saving back.
- If the REST API returns a 401, check that Application Passwords are enabled and the auth header is correct.
- If CSS doesn't apply, check selector specificity — Elementor inline styles may need `!important` overrides.
